 exclusion and nationalisms. This book introduces ongoing debates on the developing concept of »postmigration« and how it can be applied to arts and culture. While the concept has mainly gained traction in the cultural scene in Berlin, Germany, the contributions expand the field of study by attending to cultural expressions in literature, theatre, film, and art across various European societies, such as the United Kingdom, France, Finland, Denmark, and Germany. By doing so, they highlight this concept's potential and show how it can offer new perspectives on transformations caused by migration.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aArtszEuropexHistory. 0aCulture. 0aPolitics and culturezEurope. 0aSocial sciences. 4aArt. 4aCultural Studies. 4aCulture. 4aEurope. 4aInterculturalism. 4aMigration. 4aPostmigrant Society. 4aPostmigration. 4aTheatre. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Popular Culture.2bisacsh  aArt.  aCultural Studies.  aCulture.  aEurope.  aInterculturalism.  aMigration.  aPostmigrant Society.  aPostmigration.  aTheatre.1 aBromley, Roger, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBöhme, Claudia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDirckinck-Holmfeld, Katrine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEspahangizi, Kijan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGaonkar, Anna Meera, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGaonkar, Anna Meera, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHallensleben, Markus, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/voc